         <abstract>
            <p>This study shows that options listing significantly affects the spreads on the underlying stock. We identify a trade-off between the benefits of increased liquidity and the cost of informational externalities. Highly liquid stocks tend to have spread increases, while illiquid stocks experience spread decreases. The effect occurs in concert with nonlisting volatility changes. The spread changes do not appear to be caused by shifts in liquidity between the stock and options market. Often, spread changes are large enough to affect significantly the cost of equity capital.</p>
         </abstract>
